 12	/**
 13	 * Branch 6.2 — the generic action skeleton.
 14	 *
 15	 * `formAction({ form, notify, success })` collapses the `parse → decode → notify
 16	 * → toast.redirect` pipeline the three form routes triplicate into one wrapped
 17	 * route action. These tests pin the pipeline WIRING (`prove-it-works`) — the
 18	 * per-kind decode semantics are covered exhaustively in `decode.test.ts`, so here
 19	 * the form is `contact` (its graph populated in 6.3) driven by a minimal VALID
 20	 * contact payload. Every form now carries a populated graph (registration's
 21	 * migrated in 6.5), so the skeleton is isolated with a payload that decodes rather
 22	 * than the old empty-graph fixture. Each form is exercised end-to-end by its own
 23	 * equivalence harness; here we pin only the skeleton's own wiring:
 24	 *   - a valid submission runs `notify` with the decoded payload, then redirects
 25	 *     with the success toast (so a migrated route's success path is unchanged);
 26	 *   - a `notify` failure (e.g. a mailer error mapped to a form-level key) aborts
 27	 *     the redirect and surfaces as a form error report — the record-vs-notify
 28	 *     separation Branch 7 builds the persist step in front of;
 29	 *   - the honeypot short-circuit (inherited from `routeFormAction`) skips the
 30	 *     body entirely.
 31	 *
 32	 * The action runs through the real request runtime (`makeRequestRuntime`), which
 33	 * wires `Content` (reading the bundled default form definition), `Toast`, and the
 34	 * `Mailer` — the same layers the live server provides.
 35	 */
